{{Short description|Shinto shrine in Sapporo, Hokkaido, Japan}} {{Infobox religious building | name = {{Nihongo|'''Hokkaidō Shrine'''|北海道神宮|Hokkaidō Jingū}} | image = Hokkaido Jingu.JPG | caption = Hokkaido Shrine | map_type = Japan | map_alt = | coordinates = {{coord|43|3|15.24697|N|141|18|27.73923|E|type:landmark_scale:1_region:JP-01_source:dewiki|display=title,inline}} | map_relief = | map_size = | map_caption = | religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] | type = | deity = {{ill|Ōkunitama|simple|Kunitama Omikami|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōkunitama|qq=}}, [[Ōkuninushi]], and [[Sukunabikona|Sukunahikona]] | founded_by = | established = 1871 | date_destroyed = | location = {{ill|Maruyama Park (Sapporo)|en|Maruyama Park (Sapporo)|qid=Q6778052|lt=Maruyama Park|1=Maruyama Park (Sapporo)}}, 474 Miyagaoka, {{ill|Chūō-ku, Sapporo|en|Chūō-ku, Sapporo|qid=Q1079635|lt=Chūō-ku, Sapporo|1=Chūō-ku, Sapporo}}, [[:en:Hokkaidō|Hokkaidō]] 064-8505, {{ill|Japan|en|Japan|qid=Q17|lt=Japan|1=Japan}} | website = | architecture_style = | festival = | leadership = }}
The {{Nihongo|'''Hokkaidō Shrine'''|北海道神宮|Hokkaidō Jingū}}, named the {{Nihongo|'''Sapporo Shrine'''|札幌神社|Sapporo Jinja}} until 1964, is a [[Shinto]] shrine located in {{ill|Sapporo|en|Sapporo|qid=Q37951|lt=Sapporo|1=Sapporo}}, [[:en:Hokkaidō|Hokkaidō]], {{ill|Japan|en|Japan|qid=Q17|lt=Japan|1=Japan}}. Sited in {{ill|Maruyama Park (Sapporo)|en|Maruyama Park (Sapporo)|qid=Q6778052|lt=Maruyama Park|1=Maruyama Park (Sapporo)}}, {{ill|Chūō-ku, Sapporo|en|Chūō-ku, Sapporo|qid=Q1079635|lt=Chūō-ku|1=Chūō-ku, Sapporo}}, {{ill|Sapporo|en|Sapporo|qid=Q37951|lt=Sapporo|1=Sapporo}}, [[:en:Hokkaidō|Hokkaidō]], the Hokkaido Shrine enshrines four ''[[kami]]'' including the soul of the {{ill|Emperor Meiji|en|Emperor Meiji|qid=Q174231|lt=Emperor Meiji|1=Emperor Meiji}}. A number of early explorers of Hokkaidō such as [[Mamiya Rinzō]] are also enshrined.
==History== In 1869, by an order of the Emperor Meiji, a ceremony to enshrine three kami (Shinto deities); {{ill|Ōkunitama|simple|Kunitama Omikami|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōkunitama|qq=}}, [[Ōkuninushi]], and [[Sukunabikona|Sukunahikona]], was held in {{ill|Tokyo|en|Tokyo|qid=Q1490|lt=Tokyo|1=Tokyo}}. They were enshrined as the {{Nihongo|three pioneer kami|開拓三神|Kaitaku Sanjin}}, and they were later moved to Sapporo by officers in the Kaitakushi, the previous government of Hokkaidō prefecture.<ref name=History>[http://www.hokkaidojingu.or.jp/deity/index.html Hokkaido Jingu, History of the Hokkaido Jingu and kami] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012071453/http://www.hokkaidojingu.or.jp/deity/index.html |date=2007-10-12 }}</ref> An interim building of the shrine for three kami was constructed in 1870 in Sapporo, although its location was different from the current point where the Hokkaidō Shrine stands. In 1871, the shrine was erected in its current place and named "Sapporo Shrine" (Sapporo Jinja),<ref name=History/> and on September 14 an inaugural ceremony was held.
The three pioneer kami were important in the development of a "pioneer theology" which was significant to the early development of {{ill|State Shinto|en|State Shinto|qid=Q1197248|lt=State Shinto|1=State Shinto}}.<ref name=":12">{{Cite book |last=Shimizu |first=Karli |url=https://www.amazon.com/Overseas-Shinto-Shrines-Secularity-Bloomsbury/dp/1350234982 |title=Overseas Shinto Shrines: Religion, Secularity and the Japanese Empire |last2=Rambelli |first2=Fabio |date=2022-10-06 |publisher=Bloomsbury Academic |isbn=978-1-350-23498-7 |location=London New York (N.Y.) Oxford |pages= |language=English}}</ref>{{rp|61}}<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal |last1=Kōji |first1=Suga |last2=𳜳𨀉𠄈 |date=2010 |title=A Concept of "Overseas Shinto Shrines": A Pantheistic Attempt by Ogasawara Shōzō and Its Limitations |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/27822899 |journal=Japanese Journal of Religious Studies |volume=37 |issue=1 |pages=47–74 |issn=0304-1042 |jstor=27822899}}</ref>{{rp|53–54}}
In 1964, ''Sapporo-jinja'' was renamed the "Hokkaidō Shrine" (Hokkaidō Jingū) and officially upgraded to one of the {{nihongo|''[[Modern system of Ranked Shinto Shrines|Kanpei-taisha]]''|官幣大社}}, meaning that it stood in the first Rank of government supported shrines.<ref>Ponsonby-Fane, Richard. (1963). [https://books.google.com/books?id=Uru8GMeblXgC&q=sapporo+shrine+yoshihisa-shinno ''The Vicissitudes of Shinto,'' p. 328.]</ref> The soul of Emperor Meiji was also newly enshrined there in 1964.<ref name="History" /> The building was destroyed by a fire in 1974, but was later restored in 1978.
==Overview== The area of the Hokkaido Shrine is 180,000 m<sup>2</sup>,<ref name=History/> and is adjacent to {{ill|Maruyama Park (Sapporo)|en|Maruyama Park (Sapporo)|qid=Q6778052|lt=Maruyama Park|1=Maruyama Park (Sapporo)}}. During the season which {{ill|Cherry blossom|en|Cherry blossom|qid=Q871991|lt=Cherry blossom|1=Cherry blossom}}s in the area bloom, the shrine is crowded with people enjoying {{ill|Hanami|en|Hanami|qid=Q210150|lt=Hanami|1=Hanami}}. Many people also visit the shrine during [[Japanese New Year]] to go {{ill|Hatsumōde|en|Hatsumōde|qid=Q1032381|lt=Hatsumōde|1=Hatsumōde}}.
From June 14 to 16 in every year, the Main festival of Hokkaido Shrine, also called "Sapporo Festival" (Sapporo Matsuri), is held, and the line of people bearing [[Mikoshi]] parades down the street which leads to the shrine. It also manages {{ill|Scouting|en|Scouting|qid=Q872181|lt=Scouting|1=Scouting}} activities.<ref>[http://www.hokkaidojingu.or.jp/boy/index.html 1st Boyscouting in Sapporo] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071102131158/http://www.hokkaidojingu.or.jp/boy/index.html |date=2007-11-02 }}</ref>
